## Example 4 — Solve an Exponential Inequality by Using Logarithms

Solve:

`6^(2y - 5) < 5^(3y)`

Round to the nearest ten-thousandth.

Take common logarithms:

`log(6^(2y - 5)) < log(5^(3y))`

Apply the Power Property:

`(2y - 5) log 6 < 3y log 5`

Distribute:

`2y log 6 - 5 log 6 < 3y log 5`

Move the `y`-terms:

`-5 log 6 < y(3 log 5 - 2 log 6)`

Solve:

`(-5 log 6) / (3 log 5 - 2 log 6) < y`

`y > -7.1970`

### Check

Test `y = 0`:

`6^(2(0) - 5) < 5^(3(0))`

`6^(-5) < 1`

`1/7776 < 1`

This is true.

### Watch Out

When multiplying or dividing an inequality by a negative value, the inequality sign reverses. Evaluate expressions if needed to confirm the sign.

